{
  "texts": [
    "We use density functional perturbation theory 57 to predict piezoelectric and dielectric constants with electronic and ionic contributions.",
    "The linear response theory-based 58 frequency based dielectric function was calculated using OptB88vdW and TBmBJ, and the zero energy values are used to train ML models.",
    "The TBmBJ frequency-dependent dielectric function is used to calculate the maximum efficiency limited by the spectrum (SLME) 59.",
    "The magnetic moment is calculated using spin-polarized calculations considering only ferromagnetic initial configurations and ignoring any DFT + U effects.",
    "Thermoelectric coefficients such as the Seebeck coefficient and power factor are calculated using the BoltzTrap software 60 with a constant relaxation time approximation."
  ]
}